


1. What is Helm
Concept
Helm (Kubernetes package manager) is a tool used to package, deploy, and manage Kubernetes applications.
It works like a package manager for Kubernetes, similar to:
System	Package Manager
Linux	apt / yum
Python	pip
NodeJS	npm
Kubernetes	Helm
Helm simplifies deployment of complex applications with many resources.
________________________________________
2. Helm Core Concepts
Helm introduces several important concepts.
1️⃣ Chart
A Chart is a package containing Kubernetes manifests.
It includes:
•	Deployments
•	Services
•	ConfigMaps
•	Routes
•	Secrets
Example:
nginx-chart
wordpress-chart
mysql-chart
Charts make it easy to share applications.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Release
A Release is a running instance of a Helm chart.
Example:
Chart:
wordpress-chart
You can deploy it multiple times:
release1
release2
release3
Each deployment = one release.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Chart Versions
Charts have versions.
Example:
wordpress-chart v1.0
wordpress-chart v1.1
wordpress-chart v2.0
Versions allow upgrades.
________________________________________
3. Helm Chart Structure
A Helm chart has a specific directory structure.
Example:
sample/
├── Chart.yaml
├── values.yaml
└── templates/
      example.yaml
________________________________________
Chart.yaml
Contains metadata about the chart.
Example:
name: examplechart
version: 0.1.0
description: A Helm chart for Kubernetes
Fields:
Field	Meaning
name	chart name
version	chart version
description	description
maintainers	authors
________________________________________
templates/
This directory contains Kubernetes resource definitions.
Example:
Deployment
Service
ConfigMap
Route
Helm uses Go templates to dynamically generate resources.
Example:
image: {{ .Values.image.repository }}
This reads values from values.yaml.
________________________________________
values.yaml
Contains default configuration values.
Example:
image:
  repository: nginx
  tag: 1.8.10
  pullPolicy: IfNotPresent
These values can be overridden during deployment.
________________________________________
4. Inspecting Helm Charts
Before deploying a chart, you should inspect it.
________________________________________
View Chart Metadata
Command:
helm show chart chart-name
Example output:
name: examplechart
version: 0.1.0
description: A Helm chart for Kubernetes
Shows:
•	chart name
•	version
•	maintainers
•	source repo
________________________________________
View Default Values
Command:
helm show values chart-name
Example output:
image:
  repository: sample
  tag: 1.8.10
This helps you know which values you can customize.
________________________________________
5. Installing Helm Charts
Helm uses the helm install command.
Syntax:
helm install RELEASE_NAME CHART
Example:
helm install my-release nginx-chart
Explanation:
Component	Meaning
my-release	release name
nginx-chart	chart name
Helm then creates:
deployments
services
pods
configmaps
________________________________________
6. Choosing Namespace
Helm deployments usually run in a specific namespace.
Example:
helm install my-release nginx-chart --namespace myproject
If resources in the chart do not define namespaces, Helm places them in the target namespace.
________________________________________
7. Customizing Chart Values
You can override default values.
There are two ways:
Method 1 — values.yaml file
Example file:
image:
  tag: "1.8.10-patched"
Install chart:
helm install my-release nginx-chart \
--values my-values.yaml
________________________________________
Method 2 — command line
Example:
helm install my-release nginx-chart \
--set image.tag=1.8.10-patched
________________________________________
8. Preview Installation (Dry Run)
You can preview what Helm will create.
Command:
helm install my-release nginx-chart \
--dry-run --values my-values.yaml
Output includes:
MANIFEST:
Deployment
Service
ConfigMap
No resources are created.
This is useful for testing configurations.
________________________________________
9. Helm Releases
When a chart is installed:
✔ Kubernetes resources are created
✔ Helm creates a release record
Release information is stored in:
Kubernetes Secret
Type:
helm.sh/release.v1
________________________________________
10. View Releases
Command:
helm list
Example output:
NAME        NAMESPACE   STATUS
my-release  example     deployed
Options:
Command	Description
helm list	releases in current namespace
helm list --all-namespaces	releases in cluster
helm list -n namespace	releases in namespace
________________________________________
⚠️ Important
Do NOT delete Helm release secrets manually.
If deleted:
Helm cannot manage the release anymore.
________________________________________
11. Upgrading Releases
To update an application:
helm upgrade release-name chart
Example:
helm upgrade my-release nginx-chart \
--values new-values.yaml
This updates:
•	configuration values
•	chart version
•	application version
________________________________________
Preview Upgrade
Always preview changes:
helm upgrade my-release nginx-chart \
--dry-run
This prevents mistakes.
________________________________________
12. Helm Revision History
Helm tracks release changes.
Command:
helm history release-name
Example:
REVISION STATUS
1        installed
2        upgraded
Each update creates a new revision.
________________________________________
13. Rollback Releases
If an upgrade fails, you can rollback.
Command:
helm rollback release-name revision
Example:
helm rollback my-release 1
This restores revision 1.
________________________________________
⚠️ Important
Rollback may cause problems if:
•	database schema changed
•	incompatible versions exist
Always test rollback in staging.
________________________________________
14. Helm Repositories
Helm charts are usually stored in repositories.
Example repository:
https://charts.openshift.io
________________________________________
Add Repository
helm repo add openshift-helm-charts \
https://charts.openshift.io/
________________________________________
List Repositories
helm repo list
________________________________________
Update Repository
helm repo update
Updates chart index.
________________________________________
Search Charts
helm search repo
Example:
NAME
repo/nginx
repo/mysql
repo/postgres
________________________________________
Show All Chart Versions
helm search repo nginx --versions
________________________________________
Install Specific Version
helm install my-release nginx \
--version 1.2.0
________________________________________
15. Using Helm in the OpenShift Web Console
In Red Hat OpenShift Web Console, Helm can be managed from the Developer perspective.
Steps:
1️⃣ Switch to Developer perspective
2️⃣ Click Add
3️⃣ Select Developer Catalog
4️⃣ Filter:
Type → Helm Charts
5️⃣ Select chart
6️⃣ Click:
Install Helm Chart
________________________________________
During installation you configure:
Setting	Description
Release Name	unique deployment name
Namespace	project
Values	configuration values
Chart Version	version to deploy
________________________________________
16. Managing Helm Releases in Console
The console provides:
Helm Page
Shows:
Release name
Status
Revision
Chart version
________________________________________
Topology View
Shows visual graph of:
Helm Release
 ├── Deployment
 ├── Service
 ├── Route
 └── Pods
________________________________________
Release Details Page
Shows:
Section	Description
Details	chart version and status
Resources	Kubernetes resources
Release History	upgrades and rollbacks
Upgrade	update chart
Rollback	revert version
Notes	installation notes
________________________________________
17. Upgrading a Release in Console
Steps:
1️⃣ Go to Helm page
2️⃣ Select release
3️⃣ Click Upgrade
4️⃣ Modify:
•	chart version
•	values.yaml
5️⃣ Click Upgrade
A new revision is created.
________________________________________
18. Rolling Back a Release
Steps:
1️⃣ Go to Helm page
2️⃣ Open release
3️⃣ Go to Revision History
4️⃣ Select revision
5️⃣ Click Rollback
Helm restores previous version.
________________________________________
19. Uninstalling a Helm Release
To remove the application:
CLI command:
helm uninstall release-name
Example:
helm uninstall my-release
This deletes:
deployments
services
pods
routes
⚠️ Warning
If the chart deletes PVCs:
persistent data may be lost
________________________________________
20. Helm Workflow in Production
Typical workflow:
1️⃣ Add repository
helm repo add
2️⃣ Search chart
helm search repo
3️⃣ Inspect chart
helm show values
4️⃣ Create values file
my-values.yaml
5️⃣ Install chart
helm install
6️⃣ Upgrade chart
helm upgrade
7️⃣ Rollback if needed
helm rollback
________________________________________
Templates vs Helm (Important)
Feature	OpenShift Templates	Helm
Package manager	No	Yes
Versioning	No	Yes
Complex apps	Limited	Excellent
Community support	Low	Very High
Helm is now the most common method for deploying Kubernetes apps.
